Here is a Java code snippet that splits the string `a` into an array of strings using a comma and a space (", ") as the delimiter, regardless of the number of values:

```
public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        String a = "USA, Ca, NY, TX";
        String[] splitStrings = a.split(", ");
        if (splitStrings.length > 0) {
            for (int i = 0; i < splitStrings.length; i++) {
                System.out.println("String " + (i + 1) + ": " + splitStrings[i]);
            }
        } else {
            System.out.println("String is empty.");
        }
    }
}
```

In this code:

- We use the `split()` method to split the string `a` into an array of strings using ", " as the delimiter.
- We check if the length of the resulting array is greater than 0.
- If it is, we iterate over the array using a for loop and print each string.
- If not, we print a message indicating that the string is empty.

This code will work for any number of comma-separated values in the string `a`.
